Sheet, and More Financials.

117
00:04:22,530 --> 00:04:25,410
This pulls up a pretty
complicated looking page,

118
00:04:25,410 --> 00:04:28,200
but trust me, it is actually very simple.

119
00:04:28,200 --> 00:04:30,210
To help you understand this balance sheet,

120
00:04:30,210 --> 00:04:33,000
think of it like a cookie jar.

121
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:33,833
There you go.

122
00:04:33,833 --> 00:04:36,360
At the top, you've got the current assets.

123
00:04:36,360 --> 00:04:39,320
These are like the cookies
you can grab and eat.

124
00:04:39,320 --> 00:04:40,530
(cookie crunches)

125
00:04:40,530 --> 00:04:42,180
Mm, very nice.

126
00:04:42,180 --> 00:04:44,580
For a company, this is the cash,

127
00:04:44,580 --> 00:04:48,120
or anything that can be turned
into cash within 12 months.

128
00:04:48,120 --> 00:04:50,310
Next, you have the longer term assets.

129
00:04:50,310 --> 00:04:53,550
These are like the cookies
that are deeper down in a jar.

130
00:04:53,550 --> 00:04:55,560
For a company, this often includes

131
00:04:55,560 --> 00:04:57,570
the headquarters and equipment.

132
00:04:57,570 --> 00:05:00,270
Here, you have the intangible assets.

133
00:05:00,270 --> 00:05:02,100
These are like the invisible things

134
00:05:02,100 --> 00:05:04,290
that make the cookies taste good.

135
00:05:04,290 --> 00:05:06,000
You can't touch these things,

136
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:07,830
but they bring a lot of value.

137
00:05:07,830 --> 00:05:11,100
For a company, this is
patents, intellectual property,

138
00:05:11,100 --> 00:05:12,780
trademarks, and goodwill.

139
00:05:12,780 --> 00:05:15,900
This next section is
all about liabilities.

140
00:05:15,900 --> 00:05:18,390
These are like the cookies
that you've promised

141
00:05:18,390 --> 00:05:20,880
to your friends for
borrowing their ingredients.

142
00:05:20,880 --> 00:05:24,390
I'm most interested in
the current liabilities

143
00:05:24,390 --> 00:05:27,060
as these will need to be
paid back within one year

144
00:05:27,060 --> 00:05:29,580
or a normal operating cycle.

145
00:05:29,580 --> 00:05:32,880
So now you know what all
of this information means,

146
00:05:32,880 --> 00:05:34,830
what should you actually do with it?

147
00:05:34,830 --> 00:05:37,350
Well, there's a simple
calculation you can do

148
00:05:37,350 --> 00:05:40,740
to easily know if a company
is high risk or not,

149
00:05:40,740 --> 00:05:43,830
and that is total current assets

150
00:05:43,830 --> 00:05:47,430
divided by total current liabilities.

151
00:05:47,430 --> 00:05:50,550
A good rule of thumb is this
number should be above one.

152
00:05:50,550 --> 00:05:52,950
But how does this
actually work in practice?

153
00:05:52,950 --> 00:05:55,800
Well, let's put Coca-Cola's numbers in.

154
00:05:55,800 --> 00:06:00,800
Their total current
assets are $26.73 billion.

155
00:06:01,020 --> 00:06:05,940
So if we divide that by their
total current liabilities,

156
00:06:05,940 --> 00:06:10,200
which are $23.57 billion,

157
00:06:10,200 --> 00:06:13,800
that comes to approximately 1.13.

158
00:06:13,800 --> 00:06:18,060
This means the company
has $1.3 in current assets

159
00:06:18,060 --> 00:06:21,270
for every $1 in current liabilities,

160
00:06:21,270 --> 00:06:24,120
indicating they have
enough short-term assets

161
00:06:24,120 --> 00:06:25,830
to cover their short-term debts.

162
00:06:25,830 --> 00:06:27,660
This is a great indicator,

163
00:06:27,660 --> 00:06:29,745
but our work is far from over.

164
00:06:29,745 --> 00:06:30,578
(cookie crunches)

165
00:06:30,578 --> 00:06:31,411
Mm.

166
00:06:31,411 --> 00:06:33,570
(light upbeat music)

167
00:06:33,570 --> 00:06:35,130
When you're getting to know someone new,

168
00:06:35,130 --> 00:06:38,460
you're probably curious about
their past relationships.

169
00:06:38,460 --> 00:06:40,830
It's like doing a bit of
a background check, right?

170
00:06:40,830 --> 00:06:42,900
You might wonder whether
they've ever cheated

171
00:06:42,900 --> 00:06:44,700
or how many partners they've had.

172
00:06:44,700 --> 00:06:47,610
It's pretty much the same when
you're considering investing.

173
00:06:47,610 --> 00:06:50,640
Before you put your hard
earned cash into a company,

174
00:06:50,640 --> 00:06:52,710
you wanna check out its track record.

175
00:06:52,710 --> 00:06:55,680
That's where the income
statement comes in.

176
00:06:55,680 --> 00:06:59,310
And unlike people, public
companies have to be upfront

177
00:06:59,310 --> 00:07:01,170
and honest about their past.

178
00:07:01,170 --> 00:07:04,290
An income statement is like
a report card for a company

179
00:07:04,290 --> 00:07:06,960
showing how well it did
over a specific period,

180
00:07:06,960 --> 00:07:09,900
like a month, a quarter, or a year.

181
00:07:09,900 --> 00:07:13,140
Put simply, it tells you how
much money the company made

182
00:07:13,140 --> 00:07:14,640
and how much it spent.

183
00:07:14,640 --> 00:07:16,560
This is normally found in the same place

184
00:07:16,560 --> 00:07:18,000
as the balance sheet.

185
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:21,090
If you're using the
Trading 212 app like me,

186
00:07:21,090 --> 00:07:23,610
then just click on the first tab

187
00:07:23,610 --> 00:07:26,130
and then you'll see all the information.

188
00:07:26,130 --> 00:07:28,800
Here at the top, we
have the total revenue,

189
00:07:28,800 --> 00:07:32,430
which is the total the business
took in the time period.

190
00:07:32,430 --> 00:07:34,470
As we can see from Coca-Cola,

191
00:07:34,470 --> 00:07:38,820
they took 45.75 billion in 2023,

192
00:07:39,990 --> 00:07:41,670
which isn't too shabby.

193
00:07:41,670 --> 00:07:44,580
If we scroll down a bit,
we get to the net income,

194
00:07:44,580 --> 00:07:46,320
which is the money the company makes

195
00:07:46,320 --> 00:07:49,140
after all expenses have been deducted.

196
00:07:49,140 --> 00:07:54,140
For Coca-Cola, this is $10.71 billion.

197
00:07:54,780 --> 00:07:56,940
So, why does this matter?

198
00:07:56,940 --> 00:08:00,930
Well, every business has
two main types of expenses:

199
00:08:00,930 --> 00:08:04,380
the cost of revenue and
the cost of operations.

200
00:08:04,380 --> 00:08:06,120
If either of these are too high,

201
00:08:06,120 --> 00:08:08,070
then it could be a red flag.

202
00:08:08,070 --> 00:08:09,420
Just think about it.

203
00:08:09,420 --> 00:08:11,790
If you were selling custom T-shirts,

204
00:08:11,790 --> 00:08:15,000
you'd have to spend money
on fabric and printing.

205
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:16,920
This is your cost of revenue

206
00:08:16,920 --> 00:08:20,490
as you can't create custom
T-shirts without these materials,

207
00:08:20,490 --> 00:08:23,100
so this is a necessary expense.

208
00:08:23,100 --> 00:08:24,150
But that's not it.

209
00:08:24,150 --> 00:08:26,430
You'd also have to
spend money on marketing

210
00:08:26,430 --> 00:08:28,260
and potentially staff.

211
00:08:28,260 --> 00:08:31,020
These are known as your
operating expenses.

212
00:08:31,020 --> 00:08:33,750
Once you subtract both the cost of revenue

213
00:08:33,750 --> 00:08:37,260
and the operating expenses
from the total money you make

214
00:08:37,260 --> 00:08:39,630
from selling your custom T-shirts,

215
00:08:39,630 --> 00:08:41,940
you get your operating income.

216
00:08:41,940 --> 00:08:44,130
Now, if you just scale up that example,

217
00:08:44,130 --> 00:08:47,490
it's the same idea for big
companies like Coca-Cola.

218
00:08:47,490 --> 00:08:50,640
See here, this is the operating income.

219
00:08:50,640 --> 00:08:53,460
So now you know what all
this information means,

220
00:08:53,460 --> 00:08:55,080
what should you actually do with it?

221
00:08:55,080 --> 00:08:57,210
Well, here's a simple calculation to see

222
00:08:57,210 --> 00:08:59,760
if a business is making a
healthy amount of profit.

223
00:08:59,760 --> 00:09:04,530
Operating income divided by
total revenue times a hundred.

224
00:09:04,530 --> 00:09:05,910
According to Tide Banking,

225
00:09:05,910 --> 00:09:09,690
as a rule of thumb 5%
is a low profit margin,

226
00:09:09,690 --> 00:09:14,250
10% is a healthy margin,
and 20% is a high margin.

227
00:09:14,250 --> 00:09:17,490
If we plug Coca-Cola's
numbers into this calculation,

228
00:09:17,490 --> 00:09:19,000
we get approximately

229
00:09:19,889 --> 00:09:24,030
25.73%, which is a high profit margin.

230
00:09:24,030 --> 00:09:25,860
This is a great indicator to use.

231
00:09:25,860 --> 00:09:27,960
However, it's important to remember

232
00:09:27,960 --> 00:09:30,390
that older, more established companies

233
00:09:30,390 --> 00:09:32,100
will be more profitable than newer,

234
00:09:32,100 --> 00:09:33,900
faster growing companies.

235
00:09:33,900 --> 00:09:37,110
So profitability isn't
the most important thing.

236
00:09:37,110 --> 00:09:39,480
I mean, Amazon took years to make a profit

237
00:09:39,480 --> 00:09:40,470
and look at them now.

238
00:09:40,470 --> 00:09:42,930
But saying this, you
should also keep in mind

239
00:09:42,930 --> 00:09:44,970
that a company that's
done well in the past

240
00:09:44,970 --> 00:09:48,000
doesn't mean that it'll continue
to do well in the future.

241
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:51,390
Past performance doesn't
guarantee future results.

242
00:09:51,390 --> 00:09:53,310
(light upbeat music)

243
00:09:53,310 --> 00:09:56,430
Listen, it might not sound
like a romantic thing to say,

244
00:09:56,430 --> 00:09:58,830
but if you're thinking of
getting involved with someone,

245
00:09:58,830 --> 00:10:01,050
you don't want them to be bad with money.

246
00:10:01,050 --> 00:10:03,810
It can lead to a whole lot
of headaches down the line.

247
00:10:03,810 --> 00:10:04,800
Trust me.

248
00:10:04,800 --> 00:10:07,500
In fact, money issues are a huge reason

249
00:10:07,500 --> 00:10:09,480
why relationships break up.

250
00:10:09,480 --> 00:10:11,430
The same goes for companies.

251
00:10:11,430 --> 00:10:13,530
You don't wanna invest
your money in a company

252
00:10:13,530 --> 00:10:15,480
that can't handle it correctly.

253
00:10:15,480 --> 00:10:18,480
That's why you need to check
out their cash flow statement.

254
00:10:18,480 --> 00:10:21,540
Cash flow statement shows
how much money is coming in

255
00:10:21,540 --> 00:10:24,570
and going out of a company
over a period of time.

256
00:10:24,570 --> 00:10:26,820
It's divided into three parts:

257
00:10:26,820 --> 00:10:30,450
operating activities,
investing activities,

258
00:10:30,450 --> 00:10:32,400
and financing activities.

259
00:10:32,400 --> 00:10:33,450
They sound confusing,

260
00:10:33,450 --> 00:10:35,910
but trust me, they are super simple.

261
00:10:35,910 --> 00:10:37,710
Let's run through them one by one

262
00:10:37,710 --> 00:10:39,930
and I'll let you know
what to look out for.

263
00:10:39,930 --> 00:10:42,690
Operating activities show
the money a company makes

264
00:10:42,690 --> 00:10:45,120
from its regular business operations.

265
00:10:45,120 --> 00:10:48,990
In Coca-Cola's case, that's
selling their various beverages.

266
00:10:48,990 --> 00:10:50,490
All you need to look for here

267
00:10:50,490 --> 00:10:53,370
is a positive number, like this.

268
00:10:53,370 --> 00:10:55,650
It means the company is making more money

269
00:10:55,650 --> 00:10:58,650
than it spends on its
day-to-day operations.

270
00:10:58,650 --> 00:11:00,300
This is a good sign.

271
00:11:00,300 --> 00:11:02,250
Investing activity shows the money

272
00:11:02,250 --> 00:11:03,960
the company spends on investments,

273
00:11:03,960 --> 00:11:06,780
like buying new equipment, buildings,

274
00:11:06,780 --> 00:11:08,490
or other companies.

275
00:11:08,490 --> 00:11:10,230
It also includes money made

276
00:11:10,230 --> 00:11:12,570
from selling those kinds of investments.

277
00:11:12,570 --> 00:11:15,480
Believe it or not, this
negative number here

278
00:11:15,480 --> 00:11:17,010
isn't a bad thing.

279
00:11:17,010 --> 00:11:19,440
This is because the company
is re-investing back

280
00:11:19,440 --> 00:11:20,400
into the business.

281
00:11:20,400 --> 00:11:22,440
I always like it when I see that companies

282
00:11:22,440 --> 00:11:24,690
investing wisely in their future.

283
00:11:24,690 --> 00:11:27,390
Just be cautious that
they're not spending too much

284
00:11:27,390 --> 00:11:29,400
or selling off lots of assets.

285
00:11:29,400 --> 00:11:32,640
Financing activities is about
the money a company borrows

286
00:11:32,640 --> 00:11:35,400
or gets from selling
pieces of the company,

287
00:11:35,400 --> 00:11:37,740
and the money it uses to pay back loans

288
00:11:37,740 --> 00:11:40,920
or give rewards to stock owners
in the form of dividends.

289
00:11:40,920 --> 00:11:42,780
It's very important for you to keep an eye

290
00:11:42,780 --> 00:11:45,870
on how they're managing their
debt and dividend payments.

291
00:11:45,870 --> 00:11:48,810
Be cautious if they rely
too much on borrowing

292
00:11:48,810 --> 00:11:50,670
and if they're paying high dividends

293
00:11:50,670 --> 00:11:52,650
with a negative cash flow.

294
00:11:52,650 --> 00:11:54,960
It's like if you won a chunk of money

295
00:11:54,960 --> 00:11:56,340
and stopped working,

296
00:11:56,340 --> 00:11:59,433
and then kept giving all
your friends expensive gifts.

297
00:11:59,433 --> 00:12:01,470
It's just not sustainable,

298
00:12:01,470 --> 00:12:03,900
and eventually you'll run outta cash.

299
00:12:03,900 --> 00:12:07,470
However, this isn't
the case with Coca-Cola

300
00:12:07,470 --> 00:12:12,210
because even though they
gave away $7.95 billion

301
00:12:12,210 --> 00:12:14,580
worth of dividends to their shareholders,

302
00:12:14,580 --> 00:12:17,880
it's safe to say with that
kind of positive cash flow,

303
00:12:17,880 --> 00:12:19,093
they can afford it.

304
00:12:19,093 --> 00:12:21,689
(light upbeat music)

305
00:12:21,689 --> 00:12:24,420
Have you ever been really
attracted to someone online

306
00:12:24,420 --> 00:12:26,820
who seems perfect on paper,

307
00:12:26,820 --> 00:12:28,950
but when you finally meet them,

308
00:12:28,950 --> 00:12:30,690
you don't feel that spark?

309
00:12:30,690 --> 00:12:32,730
This could be similar to stocks.

310
00:12:32,730 --> 00:12:36,960
A company may appear to be a
good investment based on data,

311
00:12:36,960 --> 00:12:40,260
but there are factors that
spreadsheets just can't capture.

312
00:12:40,260 --> 00:12:42,150
That's why you need to cross examine

313
00:12:42,150 --> 00:12:45,480
with something called
qualitative analysis.

314
00:12:45,480 --> 00:12:47,460
This basically means checking out things

315
00:12:47,460 --> 00:12:48,780
that aren't numerical,

316
00:12:48,780 --> 00:12:51,480
like how well-known the company is,

317
00:12:51,480 --> 00:12:53,250
how loyal their customers are,

318
00:12:53,250 --> 00:12:56,130
and how happy those customers
are with that company.

319
00:12:56,130 --> 00:12:58,740
So yeah, it's not all about the numbers.

320
00:12:58,740 --> 00:13:01,410
You need to seek out this
information from sources

321
00:13:01,410 --> 00:13:03,600
that aren't as easy to find

322
00:13:03,600 --> 00:13:07,020
and really embody your
inner Sherlock Holmes.

323
00:13:07,020 --> 00:13:09,990
So, what information
should you be looking for

324
00:13:09,990 --> 00:13:13,440
and how can you find it when
it's not immediately obvious?

325
00:13:13,440 --> 00:13:16,320
Well, there are three key things
you need to keep an eye on.

326
00:13:16,320 --> 00:13:19,140
The first thing is brand recognition.

327
00:13:19,140 --> 00:13:21,210
If you went to a bunch
of people in the street

328
00:13:21,210 --> 00:13:23,910
and said, "Tell me what
you think about Apple,"

329
00:13:23,910 --> 00:13:26,610
you'd probably get
mostly positive responses

330
00:13:26,610 --> 00:13:30,660
about their product quality
and good privacy reputation.

331
00:13:30,660 --> 00:13:33,630
I mean, most people out
there own an Apple device

332
00:13:33,630 --> 00:13:36,570
and they've built a very
strong customer base.

333
00:13:36,570 --> 00:13:38,460
But what if I asked you about a brand

334
00:13:38,460 --> 00:13:40,980
that wasn't as popular, like Xiaomi?

335
00:13:40,980 --> 00:13:43,200
You'd probably get a
lot more blank stares,

336
00:13:43,200 --> 00:13:44,940
especially in the UK.

337
00:13:44,940 --> 00:13:46,110
If you haven't heard of it,

338
00:13:46,110 --> 00:13:47,910
it's a Chinese tech company.

339
00:13:47,910 --> 00:13:50,100
So just through those two examples,

340
00:13:50,100 --> 00:13:52,620
there is a clear contrast between the two.

341
00:13:52,620 --> 00:13:57,620
And I'd say, 99.9% of you would
rather invest in Apple stock

342
00:13:57,660 --> 00:14:00,300
just based off its brand recognition,

343
00:14:00,300 --> 00:14:03,960
even though Xiaomi is
a major player in China

344
00:14:03,960 --> 00:14:07,110
and emerging markets with
a growing customer base.

345
00:14:07,110 --> 00:14:08,670
But, why is this?

346
00:14:08,670 --> 00:14:11,460
Well, companies with a
strong brand recognition

347
00:14:11,460 --> 00:14:14,190
have built up a lot of
trust with their customers,

348
00:14:14,190 --> 00:14:17,640
meaning that they're less
impacted by any competition.

349
00:14:17,640 --> 00:14:21,060
Therefore, minimizing
your risk as an investor.

350
00:14:21,060 --> 00:14:23,640
It's like they're king on a chess board.

351
00:14:23,640 --> 00:14:26,010
Every move revolves around it

352
00:14:26,010 --> 00:14:28,530
and its position is central to the game,

353
00:14:28,530 --> 00:14:30,360
making it irreplaceable.

354
00:14:30,360 --> 00:14:32,070
The second key thing to check out

355
00:14:32,070 --> 00:14:33,900
is the company's leadership.

356
00:14:33,900 --> 00:14:35,790
You can find all this information

357
00:14:35,790 --> 00:14:38,460
by researching the company's
board of directors,

358
00:14:38,460 --> 00:14:41,040
reading transcripts of earnings calls,

359
00:14:41,040 --> 00:14:44,070
and checking out the
executive's LinkedIn profiles.

360
00:14:44,070 --> 00:14:45,870
However, it's not only important to know

361
00:14:45,870 --> 00:14:47,310
who these leaders are,

362
00:14:47,310 --> 00:14:49,740
but how long they've been working there.

363
00:14:49,740 --> 00:14:52,410
In general, the longer
they've been in charge,

364
00:14:52,410 --> 00:14:54,000
the more knowledgeable they are,

365
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:56,610
meaning the more successful
they're likely to be.

366
00:14:56,610 --> 00:14:58,710
In addition to this, lots of CEOs

367
00:14:58,710 --> 00:15:00,720
have big followings now on Twitter.

368
00:15:00,720 --> 00:15:03,900
However, this comes
with both pros and cons.

369
00:15:03,900 --> 00:15:07,170
With the power to influence
millions with just a tweet,

370
00:15:07,170 --> 00:15:09,450
it can send stock prices to the moon

371
00:15:09,450 --> 00:15:10,890
or crashing back down.

372
00:15:10,890 --> 00:15:14,557
I mean, back in 2016,
Donald Trump tweeted,

373
00:15:14,557 --> 00:15:19,110
"The F-35 program and
cost is out of control.

374
00:15:19,110 --> 00:15:22,410
Billions of dollars can and
will be saved on military

375
00:15:22,410 --> 00:15:25,867
and other purchases
after January the 20th."

376
00:15:25,867 --> 00:15:29,670
That F-35 program was a
Lockheed Martin project.

377
00:15:29,670 --> 00:15:33,000
After that tweet, Lockheed
Martin's stock price

378
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:34,440
took a nosedive.

379
00:15:34,440 --> 00:15:39,000
The company shares fell
by 2.5% on the same day,

380
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:42,750
wiping out nearly $4
billion in market value.

381
00:15:42,750 --> 00:15:44,820
So it's becoming more important than ever

382
00:15:44,820 --> 00:15:48,300
to invest in companies
with a sensible CEO.

383
00:15:48,300 --> 00:15:51,600
Otherwise, the wrong tweet
could lead to a very bumpy ride.

384
00:15:51,600 --> 00:15:53,430
The third important thing to research

385
00:15:53,430 --> 00:15:55,500
is any competitive advantages.

386
00:15:55,500 --> 00:15:59,250
So this can be things like
patents, loyal customer bases,

387
00:15:59,250 --> 00:16:01,350
or disruptive business models.

388
00:16:01,350 --> 00:16:04,380
These advantages set them
apart from the competition,

389
00:16:04,380 --> 00:16:05,940
helping them make more money

390
00:16:05,940 --> 00:16:08,790
and grow their businesses
faster over time.

391
00:16:08,790 --> 00:16:11,460
For example, Tesla has managed to secure

392
00:16:11,460 --> 00:16:13,740
a competitive advantage
through cutting edge

393
00:16:13,740 --> 00:16:15,900
electric vehicle technology

394
00:16:15,900 --> 00:16:18,750
and an expansive charging network.

395
00:16:18,750 --> 00:16:22,200
These competitive advantages
are like gold for investors

396
00:16:22,200 --> 00:16:25,890
because it means lower risk
and bigger potential rewards.

397
00:16:25,890 --> 00:16:27,720
You'll be able to find
all this information

398
00:16:27,720 --> 00:16:28,950
on the company's website

399
00:16:28,950 --> 00:16:32,010
and also through a good old Google search.

400
00:16:32,010 --> 00:16:33,600
It's time consuming, yes,

401
00:16:33,600 --> 00:16:36,270
but understanding these aspects could make

402
00:16:36,270 --> 00:16:37,590
or break your investment.

403
00:16:37,590 --> 00:16:40,200
Remember, research is your best friend.

404
00:16:40,200 --> 00:16:42,900
It's better to spend a
couple of weeks researching

405
00:16:42,900 --> 00:16:46,197
rather than make a rushed
investment and have it backfire.

406
00:16:46,197 --> 00:16:48,930
(light upbeat music)

407
00:16:48,930 --> 00:16:50,940
Let's say you hear a nasty rumor

408
00:16:50,940 --> 00:16:52,830
about the person you're seeing.

409
00:16:52,830 --> 00:16:56,910
You might panic and dump them
without getting to the truth.

410
00:16:56,910 --> 00:16:59,760
This is what so many people
do when they hear bad news

411
00:16:59,760 --> 00:17:02,070
about the company they've invested in.

412
00:17:02,070 --> 00:17:04,590
They rush to sell it
without actually giving it

413
00:17:04,590 --> 00:17:05,790
any proper thought.

414
00:17:05,790 --> 00:17:07,470
They just act on emotion.

415
00:17:07,470 --> 00:17:09,780
The news is actually so powerful.

416
00:17:09,780 --> 00:17:11,430
Think back to when the news broke

417
00:17:11,430 --> 00:17:14,490
that we might see empty
shelves in the supermarkets.

418
00:17:14,490 --> 00:17:15,840
What did everyone do?

419
00:17:15,840 --> 00:17:17,970
They panic bought toilet rolls

420
00:17:17,970 --> 00:17:20,250
until they really did run out.

421
00:17:20,250 --> 00:17:23,940
The panic buying just made
the situation so much worse.

422
00:17:23,940 --> 00:17:27,240
Just imagine if that wasn't
reported on the news,

423
00:17:27,240 --> 00:17:29,010
there wouldn't have been panic buying

424
00:17:29,010 --> 00:17:31,950
and toilet rolls wouldn't
have sold out in every store.

425
00:17:31,950 --> 00:17:34,680
The news has the same
power over investors too,

426
00:17:34,680 --> 00:17:37,590
and can cause abrupt
surges in stock prices.

427
00:17:37,590 --> 00:17:41,760
But more often than not, it
causes extreme panic selling.

428
00:17:41,760 --> 00:17:43,950
One example of panic selling is when

429
00:17:43,950 --> 00:17:48,600
the Cambridge Analytica
scandal broke in March 2018

430
00:17:48,600 --> 00:17:51,870
and personal data was unethically taken,

431
00:17:51,870 --> 00:17:56,870
causing Facebook stock to plummet
nearly 18% in just 10 days

432
00:17:57,450 --> 00:18:00,630
as investors reacted to
the news of data misuse.

433
00:18:00,630 --> 00:18:02,550
But as we can see, if we zoom out,

434
00:18:02,550 --> 00:18:06,840
since then the stock has
gone up by more than 200%.

435
00:18:06,840 --> 00:18:08,850
This was just a blip on the radar,

436
00:18:08,850 --> 00:18:11,460
and long-term investors
that understood that

437
00:18:11,460 --> 00:18:14,880
held strong because they were
confident in their research.

438
00:18:14,880 --> 00:18:17,070
So if the news is full of fearmongering,

439
00:18:17,070 --> 00:18:20,310
then how do you know when
to actually sell a stock?

440
00:18:20,310 --> 00:18:23,610
Well, there's a few occasions
when you should sell a stock,

441
00:18:23,610 --> 00:18:26,340
and this might not be what
you're expecting to hear,

442
00:18:26,340 --> 00:18:29,460
but these occasions actually depend on you

443
00:18:29,460 --> 00:18:31,290
and not the stock market.

444
00:18:31,290 --> 00:18:35,430
For example, if you find
yourself in a financial emergency

445
00:18:35,430 --> 00:18:38,730
and don't have any emergency
fund to fall back on,

446
00:18:38,730 --> 00:18:40,710
then, I'd advise you sell your shares

447
00:18:40,710 --> 00:18:43,050
to get yourself out of
that sticky situation.

448
00:18:43,050 --> 00:18:45,120
Or on a more positive note,

449
00:18:45,120 --> 00:18:47,280
maybe you've hit a financial goal

450
00:18:47,280 --> 00:18:49,020
and you'd like to take a vacation.

451
00:18:49,020 --> 00:18:51,180
I wouldn't normally
suggest this to people,

452
00:18:51,180 --> 00:18:52,920
but if it's a figure at which

453
00:18:52,920 --> 00:18:55,980
you would feel satisfied
selling a stock at,

454
00:18:55,980 --> 00:18:58,290
then do it and enjoy your gains.

455
00:18:58,290 --> 00:18:59,910
The last reason to sell a stock

456
00:18:59,910 --> 00:19:01,500
is when you no longer believe

457
00:19:01,500 --> 00:19:03,600
in the fundamentals of the company

458
00:19:03,600 --> 00:19:05,730
and their future trajectory.

459
00:19:05,730 --> 00:19:09,052
In this case, it may
be time to cut and run.

460
00:19:09,052 --> 00:19:11,880
(light upbeat music)

461
00:19:11,880 --> 00:19:13,350
When looking for a partner,

462
00:19:13,350 --> 00:19:16,500
you don't wanna settle with
the first person you date.

463
00:19:16,500 --> 00:19:17,910
It's important to explore

464
00:19:17,910 --> 00:19:20,160
what different people have to offer.

465
00:19:20,160 --> 00:19:21,690
Some may seem perfect,

466
00:19:21,690 --> 00:19:23,850
but too self-absorbed

467
00:19:23,850 --> 00:19:26,250
while others may have a great potential.

468
00:19:26,250 --> 00:19:27,870
The same concept applies

469
00:19:27,870 --> 00:19:30,180
when building your investment portfolio.

470
00:19:30,180 --> 00:19:33,300
The main types of stocks
are value and growth.

471
00:19:33,300 --> 00:19:35,610
It's beneficial to understand both,

472
00:19:35,610 --> 00:19:38,666
so you can decide whether
to focus on just one type

473
00:19:38,666 --> 00:19:40,050
or mix and match.

474
00:19:40,050 --> 00:19:41,730
Value stocks are normally shares

475
00:19:41,730 --> 00:19:44,070
in big, well-known companies.

476
00:19:44,070 --> 00:19:46,620
These companies have a few key features.

477
00:19:46,620 --> 00:19:49,020
First, their stock prices
are considered lower

478
00:19:49,020 --> 00:19:51,630
compared to other companies in the market.

479
00:19:51,630 --> 00:19:55,050
They also have a low
price to earnings ratio,

480
00:19:55,050 --> 00:19:56,640
which means they make good money

481
00:19:56,640 --> 00:19:58,290
compared to their stock price.

482
00:19:58,290 --> 00:20:00,240
Additionally, they're stable

483
00:20:00,240 --> 00:20:03,600
and they don't have wild ups
and downs in their stock prices

484
00:20:03,600 --> 00:20:05,220
and they pay dividends,

485
00:20:05,220 --> 00:20:07,500
which essentially means
they regularly give

486
00:20:07,500 --> 00:20:09,960
some of their profits
back to their investors.

487
00:20:09,960 --> 00:20:12,330
Value stocks are often found in companies

488
00:20:12,330 --> 00:20:13,740
that people rely on

489
00:20:13,740 --> 00:20:15,240
even when times are tough,

490
00:20:15,240 --> 00:20:17,640
like during a recession, for example.

491
00:20:17,640 --> 00:20:20,610
These companies make or
provide things that people need

492
00:20:20,610 --> 00:20:21,570
no matter what.

493
00:20:21,570 --> 00:20:23,970
Examples include consumer staples,

494
00:20:23,970 --> 00:20:27,390
which are everyday products
like food and household items,

495
00:20:27,390 --> 00:20:30,480
energy companies that
provide fuel and power,

496
00:20:30,480 --> 00:20:32,760
financials like banks,

497
00:20:32,760 --> 00:20:36,480
and industrials that build
things and provide raw materials.

498
00:20:36,480 --> 00:20:38,940
Some well-known examples of value stocks

499
00:20:38,940 --> 00:20:42,240
are Berkshire Hathaway, which
is owned by Warren Buffet

500
00:20:42,240 --> 00:20:44,970
and invest in many different companies;

501
00:20:44,970 --> 00:20:47,970
Procter & Gamble, which
makes everyday products

502
00:20:47,970 --> 00:20:49,830
like shampoo and toothpaste;

503
00:20:49,830 --> 00:20:52,380
and JP Morgan, a major bank.

504
00:20:52,380 --> 00:20:54,030
Growth stocks, on the other hand,

505
00:20:54,030 --> 00:20:57,570
are usually seen as overvalued
compared to the market.

506
00:20:57,570 --> 00:20:59,490
They tend to be pretty volatile,

507
00:20:59,490 --> 00:21:02,430
meaning their stock prices
can go up and down a lot.

508
00:21:02,430 --> 00:21:05,670
These stocks have higher
price earnings ratios.

509
00:21:05,670 --> 00:21:07,530
This means that investors expect them

510
00:21:07,530 --> 00:21:09,600
to grow a lot in the future

511
00:21:09,600 --> 00:21:11,910
and they pay little to no dividends.

512
00:21:11,910 --> 00:21:15,750
Some growth stocks aren't even
profitable for a long time

513
00:21:15,750 --> 00:21:19,050
as they reinvest their earnings
to fuel further growth.

514
00:21:19,050 --> 00:21:22,170
Growth stocks are expected
to grow at a more rapid pace

515
00:21:22,170 --> 00:21:23,850
than the overall market,

516
00:21:23,850 --> 00:21:27,360
which is why they often
outperform the market.

517
00:21:27,360 --> 00:21:29,520
Some well-known examples of growth stocks

518
00:21:29,520 --> 00:21:33,870
include Amazon, Meta
Platforms, NVIDIA, and Tesla.

519
00:21:33,870 --> 00:21:36,780
If you're not sure if the
stock is growth or value,

520
00:21:36,780 --> 00:21:40,890
then a quick way to tell
is by using the P/E ratio.

521
00:21:40,890 --> 00:21:44,250
You can easily find this
here on Trading 212.

522
00:21:44,250 --> 00:21:49,250
Typically, the average P/E
ratio is around 20 to 25.

523
00:21:49,320 --> 00:21:52,020
Anything below that
would be considered good,

524
00:21:52,020 --> 00:21:54,420
whereas anything above would be worse.

525
00:21:54,420 --> 00:21:56,520
However, this is just
a general rule of thumb

526
00:21:56,520 --> 00:21:58,950
and does vary depending on the industry,

527
00:21:58,950 --> 00:22:00,300
so make sure to compare it

528
00:22:00,300 --> 00:22:02,520
with some other companies in that sector.

529
00:22:02,520 --> 00:22:03,870
Once you've determined whether you're

530
00:22:03,870 --> 00:22:06,690
a value, growth, or mixed investor,

531
00:22:06,690 --> 00:22:07,920
you need to ensure you have

532
00:22:07,920 --> 00:22:10,890
a diverse range of
stocks in your portfolio.

533
00:22:10,890 --> 00:22:13,480
This is what we call diversification.

534
00:22:13,480 --> 00:22:16,170
So if one of your stocks takes a dive,

535
00:22:16,170 --> 00:22:18,660
your banking on the others
to balance things out.

536
00:22:18,660 --> 00:22:21,330
A general rule is not to have more than 5%

537
00:22:21,330 --> 00:22:23,370
of your money in one stock

538
00:22:23,370 --> 00:22:27,570
and no more than 20% of your
investments in one sector,

539
00:22:27,570 --> 00:22:30,060
such as technology, for example.

540
00:22:30,060 --> 00:22:31,560
It's a good idea to have stocks

541
